SIMPLE: fool
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fool
<hw>Fool</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>fouler</ets>
to tread, crush. Cf. 1st <er>Foil</er>.]</ety> <def>A compound of
gooseberries scalded and crushed, with cream; -- commonly called
<xex>gooseberry fool</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fool</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fool
<hw>Fool</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>fol</ets>, n. & adj., F.
<ets>fol</ets>, <ets>fou</ets>, foolish, mad; a fool, prob. fr. L.
<ets>follis</ets> a bellows, wind bag, an inflated ball; perh. akin to
E. <ets>bellows</ets>. Cf. <er>Folly</er>, <er>Follicle</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>One destitute of reason, or of the common powers of
understanding; an idiot; a natural.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A person deficient in intellect; one who acts
absurdly, or pursues a course contrary to the dictates of wisdom; one
without judgment; a simpleton; a dolt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> Extol not riches, then, the toil of <qex>fools</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> Experience keeps a dear school, but <qex>fools</qex> will learn
in no <qex>other</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Franklin.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Script.)</fld> <def>One who acts contrary to moral
and religious wisdom; a wicked person.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> The <qex>fool</qex> hath said in his heart, There is no God.</q>
<rj><qau>Ps. xiv. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>One who counterfeits folly; a professional jester or
buffoon; a retainer formerly kept to make sport, dressed fantastically
in motley, with ridiculous accouterments.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> Can they think me . . . their <qex>fool</qex> or jester?</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>April fool</b></col>, <col><b>Court fool</b></col>,
etc.</mcol> <cd>See under <er>April</er>, <er>Court</er>, etc.</cd> --
<col><b>Fool's cap</b></col>, <cd>a cap or hood to which bells were
usually attached, formerly worn by professional jesters.</cd> --
<col><b>Fool's errand</b></col>, <cd>an unreasonable, silly, profitless
adventure or undertaking.</cd> -- <col><b>Fool's gold</b></col>,
<cd>iron or copper pyrites, resembling gold in color.</cd> --
<col><b>Fool's paradise</b></col>, <cd>a name applied to a limbo (see
under <er>Limbo</er>) popularly believed to be the region of vanity and
nonsense. Hence, any foolish pleasure or condition of vain
self-satistaction.</cd> -- <col><b>Fool's parsley</b></col>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>an annual umbelliferous plant (<spn>Aethusa
Cynapium</spn>) resembling parsley, but nauseous and poisonous.</cd> --
<col><b>To make a fool of</b></col>, <cd>to render ridiculous; to
outwit; to shame.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> -- <col><b>To play the
fool</b></col>, <cd>to act foolishly; to act the buffoon; to act a
foolish part.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧I have <xex>played the fool</xex>, and have
erred exceedingly.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>1 Sam. xxvi. 21.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fool</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fool
<hw>Fool</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Fooled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Fooling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To play the fool.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To waste time in unproductive activity; to spend
time in idle sport or mirth; to trifle; to toy.</def>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> fool around.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>Is this a time for <qex>fooling</qex>?</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fool</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Fool
<hw>Fool</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To infatuate; to make
foolish.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For, <qex>fooled</qex> with hope, men favor the deceit.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To use as a fool; to deceive in a shameful or
mortifying manner; to impose upon; to cheat by inspiring foolish
confidence; <as>as, to <ex>fool</ex> one out of his
money</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You are <qex>fooled</qex>, discarded, and shook off⟦br⟧
By him for whom these shames ye underwent.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To fool away</b></col>, <cd>to get rid of foolishly; to
spend in trifles, idleness, folly, or without advantage.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Foolahs</ent>⟦br⟧
